cs.CV, cs.GR, cs.MM, cs.HC, cs.AI 

The paper proposes a novel virtual reality image quality assessment (VR IQA) method using deep networks and adversarial learning. The paper focuses on the evaluation of omnidirectional images, which are commonly used in virtual reality applications. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper also involves human perception and subjective experiments, which suggest the possibility of belonging to cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction). The paper uses deep learning techniques, which could also suggest cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as a possible sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves graphics and multimedia, which could suggest cs.GR (Graphics) and cs.MM (Multimedia) as possible sub-categories.
